{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-88650f26e311a08b", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t                                         Cumsum-Composable Phase Transport\n2\t                                         for Low-Cost Streaming Keyword Spotting\n3\t\n4\t                                         Mahesh Godavarti\n5\t                                         A Carrot, Inc\n6\t\n7\t\n8\t\n9\t                                                                                            Abstract\n10\t\n11\t                                                 State-space sequence models are attractive for streaming speech because they carry a com-\n12\t                                                 pact state through time, but their training cost can depend on scan-style kernels whose\n13\t                                                 constant factors are unfavorable for short audio tasks and commodity GPUs. We study\n14\t                                                 a simpler streaming-native alternative for keyword spotting: phase-transport layers whose\n15\t                                                 products reduce to cumulative sums. Each layer maps frame features to complex channels,\n16\t                                                 transports them by learned rotations, accumulates over a finite window by prefix differences,\n17\t                                                 and then applies a gated residual update. The same representation has an exact batched\n18\tarXiv:2607.20086v1 [cs.SD] 22 Jul 2026\n19\t\n20\t\n21\t\n22\t\n23\t                                                 training form and an exact online inference form: batch training uses ordinary cumulative\n24\t                                                 sums, while streaming inference maintains the same prefix state with one update per frame\n25\t                                                 and recovers rolling windows by prefix differences. The key structural assumption is unitary\n26\t                                                 transport: inverse rotations used to build the prefix state are norm-preserving, so finite\n27\t                                                 memory is introduced by window or block readouts rather than by ill-conditioned inverse\n28\t                                                 decay factors.\n29\t                                                 On Google Speech Commands v2 with 12 labels, mel+cumsum models are competitive with\n30\t                                                 our compact convolutional baseline. The strongest single-seed mel+cumsum run reaches\n31\t                                                 97.3% test accuracy; a 51.6K-parameter tied variant reaches the same value, and a 24.8K-\n32\t                                                 parameter tied model reaches 96.8%, comparable to a 25.6K-parameter MelCNNMaxPool\n33\t                                                 baseline at 97.1%. In a matched cumsum-versus-scan benchmark with the same mel front\n34\t                                                 end, tied projections, normalization, and gating, cumsum+window gives comparable test\n35\t                                                 accuracy, 94.82% versus 94.33% for a learned-decay scan, while training 1.07x faster and\n36\t                                                 reducing single-example latency from 7.09 ms to 5.01 ms on a Tesla T4. An optimized raw-\n37\t                                                 audio cumsum front end matches mel front-end single-example latency in this setup, 337\n38\t                                                 microseconds versus 359 microseconds. Overall, cumsum-composable local transport retains\n39\t                                                 competitive keyword-spotting accuracy while replacing scan-style temporal aggregation with\n40\t                                                 ordinary cumulative sums, prefix differences, and a small streaming state.\n41\t\n42\t\n43\t                                         1   Introduction\n44\t                                         Streaming speech systems need to preserve temporal evidence while processing audio under tight latency\n45\t                                         and cost constraints. Modern state-space models (SSMs) are one answer: they replace all-pairs attention\n46\t                                         over long histories with a compact recurrent state, and selective variants can choose what to retain or forget\n47\t                                         as input arrives (Gu et al., 2022a; Smith et al., 2023; Gu & Dao, 2023). For short-window keyword spotting,\n48\t                                         however, the practical tradeoff is different. A one-second command is a finite local pattern, and compact\n49\t                                         CNNs already map well to commodity hardware (Zhang et al., 2018; Choi et al., 2019; Kim et al., 2021). If an\n50\t                                         SSM-like model requires scan kernels, repeated state updates, and nontrivial backward passes, its asymptotic\n51\t                                         linearity may not translate into low training cost on small tasks.\n52\t                                         This paper studies a cumsum-composable alternative. The central operation is a transported finite-window\n53\t                                         sum. Given complex value channels zt ∈ Cn and phase operators Ut = diag(eiϕt,1 , . . . , eiϕt,n ), define\n54\t                                                                                                t\n55\t                                                                                                X\n56\t                                                                                yt = Ut                      Uτ−1 zτ .                              (1)\n57\t                                                                                          τ =max(1,t−W +1)\n58\t\n59\t\n60\t                                                                                                 1\n61\t\fThis is a local phase-transport analogue of a recurrent memory: evidence from time τ is carried into the\n62\tcoordinate frame at time t before aggregation. When the phases are fixed or are cumulative sums of per-\n63\tframe increments, eq. (1) is computed by prefix sums and prefix differences, one of the standard primitives\n64\tfor parallel sequence computation (Blelloch, 1990). It is therefore easy to train in parallel and easy to run in\n65\tstreaming mode. The transport makes this more expressive than an ordinary cumulative sum over frames.\n66\tThe contribution of frame τ to output time t is Ut Uτ−1 zτ , so the layer computes learned relative-phase\n67\tevidence as a function of lag while still admitting a prefix representation.\n68\tThe experiments in this paper are deliberately modest. We use Google Speech Commands v2 (Warden,\n69\t2018), a short-command benchmark, to ask whether this architecture is worth studying before scaling to\n70\tfull ASR. Fixed-frequency mel+cumsum models are strong and efficient. The contribution is a practical\n71\tarchitectural result: finite-memory unitary transport gives a useful class of streaming sequence layers whose\n72\trecurrence factors exactly into prefix accumulators. The experiments show that this simpler batch and\n73\tstreaming implementation remains accurate enough to be viable on this task.\n74\t\n75\tContributions.     We make six claims, all scoped to the local experiments reported here.\n76\t\n77\t• We formulate a phase-transport layer whose finite-window representation is computed by cumulative sums\n78\t  and has an exact streaming equivalent.\n79\t• We explain why unitary transport is the structural assumption that makes the prefix factorization nu-\n80\t  merically well conditioned: the inverse transports remain bounded.\n81\t• We describe the corresponding streaming front end: audio is converted to low-latency mel or learned\n82\t  spectral frames, each frame updates the cumsum state once, and rolling keyword scores are emitted from\n83\t  finite-window states.\n84\t• We show that stacked local mel+cumsum layers are competitive with the compact CNN baseline in our\n85\t  local Speech Commands setup, reaching up to 97.3% test accuracy.\n86\t• We show that tied local cumsum layers retain strong accuracy with small parameter counts, including a\n87\t  24.8K-parameter model at 96.8%.\n88\t• We report a matched systems benchmark against a learned-decay scan layer, showing lower latency and\n89\t  comparable accuracy without a custom scan kernel.\n90\t\n91\t2     Cumsum Phase Transport\n92\t2.1    Windowed Transport by Prefix Differences\n93\t\n94\tLet zt ∈ Cn be the complex value produced from an input feature vector at time t. Let Ut ∈ Cn×n be a\n95\tdiagonal unitary transport operator. The transported finite-window sum in eq. (1) can be written with a\n96\tprefix accumulator\n97\t                                                 Xt\n98\t                                            pt =    Uτ−1 zτ .                                       (2)\n99\t                                                     τ =1\n100\tThen\n101\t                                  yt = Ut (pt − pt−W ) ,    ps = 0 for s ≤ 0.                               (3)\n102\tThis is the entire computational advantage: the layer uses a cumulative sum of transported values, a delayed\n103\tprefix subtraction, and an elementwise rotation back to the current frame.\n104\tProposition 1 (Exact batch/streaming equivalence). For fixed model parameters and a fixed input sequence,\n105\teq. (3) produces the same yt whether pt is computed by a batched cumulative sum over the whole sequence or\n106\tby the streaming update\n107\t                                             pt = pt−1 + Ut−1 zt .\n108\t                                                      Pt\n109\tProof. The streaming recurrence expands to pt = τ =1 Uτ−1 zτ , which is exactly the batched cumulative\n110\tsum. Substituting this prefix into eq. (3) gives the same finite-window transported sum.\n111\t\n112\t\n113\t                                                       2\n114\t\f2.2   Why Transport Before Accumulation?\n115\t\n116\tAn ordinary cumulative sum aggregates values in a fixed coordinate system. Temporal order enters only\n117\tthrough window membership and through nonlinear layers after the sum. Phase transport changes the\n118\toperation: the contribution from time τ to time t is\n119\t\n120\t                                                   Ut Uτ−1 zτ .\n121\t\n122\tFor fixed learned phases ϕt,k = tωk , the kth complex coordinate is weighted by ei(t−τ )ωk . The layer therefore\n123\timplements learned oscillatory kernels over relative lag, but all such kernels share a cumsum implementation\n124\tbecause each term can be moved into a common prefix coordinate system before accumulation. This is\n125\tthe modeling role of complex rotations: they make the accumulated evidence depend on relative phase,\n126\tnot only on the unordered sum of local values. Complex exponentials and rotations are standard tools in\n127\tsequence models, appearing in sinusoidal and rotary position representations as well as diagonal complex\n128\tstate-space parameterizations (Vaswani et al., 2017; Su et al., 2021; Gupta et al., 2022; Gu et al., 2022b). The\n129\tcontribution here is narrower: a finite-window, unitary transport parameterization whose online recurrence\n130\tand batched training computation are exactly the same prefix representation.\n131\t\n132\t2.3   Streaming Front End\n133\t\n134\tThe cumsum layer is naturally paired with a streaming acoustic front end. At deployment, incoming wave-\n135\tform samples are held in a short analysis buffer. Every hop, for example 80 samples (5 ms) or 160 samples\n136\t(10 ms) at 16 kHz, the front end emits one acoustic frame. That frame can be a conventional log-mel vec-\n137\ttor, as in the strongest experiments here, or a learned cumsum spectral vector as in the learned-front-end\n138\texperiments.\n139\tThe online pipeline is:\n140\t\n141\t                  x1:t → mt → zt → pt = pt−1 + Ut−1 zt → yt = Ut (pt − pt−W ) → st .\n142\t\n143\tHere mt is the acoustic frame, zt is the complex value injected into the transport layer, pt is the maintained\n144\tprefix state, yt is the current finite-window transported state, and st is a keyword logit or trigger score. The\n145\tmodel therefore does not need to wait for a full one-second clip. It can update a rolling score at the frame hop\n146\trate and emit when the score crosses a task-specific threshold. Continuous-stream keyword spotting normally\n147\trequires additional trigger metrics such as false accepts, false rejects, and detection latency (Rybakov et al.,\n148\t2020; Jose et al., 2022); the present experiments evaluate the model first as a clip classifier with an exact\n149\tstreaming implementation. Figure 1 summarizes the resulting streaming layer.\n150\tThe memory needed per layer is small. For a hard window, the implementation stores the current prefix pt\n151\tand a ring buffer of old prefixes needed to form pt − pt−W . For block decay, it stores block summaries and\n152\tupdates them at block boundaries. In both cases, online inference uses the same representation as batched\n153\ttraining; the difference is only whether prefixes are produced by a full-sequence cumulative sum or by the\n154\tone-frame recurrence.\n155\t\n156\t2.4   Fixed Learned Phases\n157\t\n158\tThe fixed-frequency models use one learned frequency per complex channel and layer:\n159\t\n160\t                                                  ϕt,k = tωk .                                              (4)\n161\t\n162\tThis gives each complex channel a learned local oscillator. The resulting rotations are unitary, so the\n163\ttransport part is norm-preserving; finite memory is supplied by the window or block-decay readout rather\n164\tthan by continuously damping the oscillator. Because the phases are deterministic functions of time within\n165\ta layer, the whole sequence can be processed by cumulative sums during training and by a one-step prefix\n166\tupdate during streaming inference.\n167\t\n168\t\n169\t                                                        3\n170\t\fTable 1: Simple fixed mel+cumsum architecture. The main experiments vary d, L, W , hop length, and\n171\twhether the projection/GLU are tied across layers.\n172\t      Component                Implementation\n173\t      Acoustic front end       40-bin log-mel spectrogram, 16 kHz audio, 400-sample FFT window, hop 80 or\n174\t                               160 samples; SpecAugment during training.\n175\t      Embedding                Linear map mt ∈ R40 to ht ∈ Rd .\n176\t      Value projection         Linear map ht 7→ (at , bt ) ∈ Rd/2 × Rd/2 , interpreted as zt = at + ibt .\n177\t      Fixed phase bank         Per-layer learned\n178\t                                              P frequencies   ωℓ,k with ϕt,k = tωℓ,k and Ut = diag(eiϕt,k ).\n179\t                                                       −1\n180\t      Cumsum transport         Compute pt = τ ≤t Uτ zτ and read out yt = Ut (pt − pt−W ).\n181\t      Layer update             Concatenate [ℜyt , ℑyt ], apply BatchNorm, GLU, and residual addition.\n182\t      Classifier               Convert final real/imaginary channels to magnitudes, max-pool over time, and\n183\t                               apply a linear 12-way classifier.\n184\t      Tied variant             Share the value projection and GLU across all layers; keep frequencies and\n185\t                               BatchNorm separate per layer.\n186\t\n187\t\n188\t2.5    Why Unitary Transport?\n189\t\n190\tThe prefix construction requires applying an inverse transport to each incoming value before accumulation.\n191\tFor unitary rotations, Ut−1 = Ut∗ and ∥Ut−1 z∥ = ∥z∥, so the prefix terms remain on the same numerical scale\n192\tas the projected values. This is the algebraic reason that batch cumsums and streaming prefix updates are\n193\tboth simple and stable.\n194\tThe contrast with decaying transport clarifies the design choice. Suppose one tried to use At = ρt Ut\n195\twith 0 < ρ < 1 in the same prefix form. The prefix accumulator would contain terms A−1       τ zτ = ρ     Uτ zτ .\n196\t                                                                                                       −τ −1\n197\t\n198\tAlthough the final readout could multiply by a small forward factor and cancel this scaling in exact arithmetic,\n199\tthe prefix state itself would involve division by progressively smaller numbers. In finite precision this can\n200\tcreate large scale separation, overflow risk, and loss of low-order information. Unitary transport avoids this\n201\tclass of conditioning issues because the inverse used to build prefixes has norm one. For this reason, forgetting\n202\tis introduced outside the transport inversion, through hard-window subtraction or block-level weighting.\n203\t\n204\t2.6    Layer Form\n205\t\n206\tThe main mel+cumsum layer follows the implementation in the local experiment code. A log-mel frame\n207\tmt ∈ R40 is embedded into ht ∈ Rd . At each cumsum layer, a linear projection creates real and imaginary\n208\tchannels:\n209\t                                    (at , bt ) = Pℓ ht , zt = at + ibt .\n210\tThe transported window sum yt is computed by eq. (3), converted back to real coordinates, normalized, and\n211\tpassed through a gated residual update:\n212\t\n213\t                                       ht ← ht + GLU(BN([ℜyt , ℑyt ])).                                        (5)\n214\t\n215\tFor windowed classification, the model collapses the final complex channels to magnitudes and applies tem-\n216\tporal max pooling. Tied variants share the projection and GLU across layers while retaining per-layer\n217\tfrequency and normalization parameters. Table 1 summarizes the simple fixed-frequency architecture used\n218\tfor the main mel+cumsum results.\n219\t\n220\t2.7    Block Decay\n221\t\n222\tHard finite windows are efficient but can be unstable because the representation changes discontinuously when\n223\tan old term exits the window. The block-decay variant replaces a single hard window with a geometrically\n224\tweighted sum of blocks:\n225\t                                             K−1\n226\t                                              X\n227\t                                     yt = Ut     λb pt−bW − pt−(b+1)W .                                    (6)\n228\t                                                                         \u0001\n229\t\n230\t                                             b=0\n231\t\n232\t\n233\t                                                       4\n234\t\f                       streaming         complex            inverse          prefix\n235\t                       frames mt       projection zt       transport       update pt\n236\t\n237\t\n238\t\n239\t                         rolling        BN + GLU           transport        window\n240\t                        score st         residual          to time t       difference\n241\t\n242\t\n243\tFigure 1: Streaming phase-transport layer. Batch training computes all prefixes by a cumulative sum;\n244\tstreaming inference maintains the same prefix state one frame at a time.\n245\t\n246\t\n247\tThis keeps the computation cumsum-based while adding smooth forgetting. The main mel experiments in\n248\tthis paper use hard windows; block decay is a cumsum-compatible alternative for settings where smoother\n249\tforgetting is useful.\n250\t\n251\t\n252\t3     Experimental Setup\n253\t\n254\tDataset. All experiments use Google Speech Commands v2 with one-second 16 kHz clips. The label set\n255\thas 12 classes: ten commands (yes, no, up, down, left, right, on, off, stop, go) plus unknown and silence.\n256\tUnknown examples are subsampled to match the average number of target-command examples; silence is\n257\tgenerated from the dataset background-noise clips.\n258\t\n259\tBaselines. We compare three families. First, compact convolutional baselines use either log-mel fea-\n260\ttures or raw waveform convolutions. The strongest mel baseline is MelCNNMaxPool, a TC-ResNet-style\n261\tone-dimensional temporal CNN over log-mel channels with SpecAugment (Choi et al., 2019; Park et al.,\n262\t2019). Published KWS systems include DS-CNN-style embedded models and stronger broadcast-residual\n263\tCNNs (Zhang et al., 2018; Kim et al., 2021); the local MelCNNMaxPool model serves as the controlled\n264\tcompact reference for the experiments below. Second, learned spectral front ends replace the fixed FFT/mel\n265\ttransform with learned sinusoidal cumsum filters, connecting this part of the study to learned audio front\n266\tends such as LEAF (Zeghidour et al., 2021). Third, a matched scan baseline keeps the same mel front end,\n267\ttied projections, normalization, and gating as the cumsum model, but replaces each hard-window cumsum\n268\twith a learned exponential-decay scan.\n269\t\n270\tTraining. Full runs use the full local training set, approximately 36K examples, for 40 or 80 epochs\n271\tdepending on the experiment. Smoke tests use a two-epoch subset of roughly 4K training examples and are\n272\tused only for architectural deconstruction. Mel/CNN models use Adam with learning rate 10−3 and weight\n273\tdecay 10−4 . All reported results in this draft are single-seed unless otherwise stated. The cumsum-versus-\n274\tscan systems benchmark was run on a Tesla T4 with CUDA 12.4, PyTorch 2.6, Torchaudio 2.6, and batch\n275\tsize 128 for training.\n276\t\n277\t\n278\t4     Results\n279\t\n280\t4.1   Mel+Cumsum Is Competitive\n281\t\n282\tTable 2 shows the strongest local mel+cumsum and CNN results. The strongest single-seed cumsum runs\n283\treach 97.3% test accuracy. A cumsum-composable temporal primitive remains comparable to the local CNN\n284\tbaseline while using an exact streaming prefix representation. Tying and small local windows preserve most\n285\tof the performance with much lower parameter counts.\n286\tThe 24.8K-parameter fixed tied model is the cleanest efficiency result: it is close to the 25.6K-parameter\n287\tMelCNNMaxPool baseline while replacing temporal convolutions after the mel front end with cumsum-\n288\tcomposable phase transport. The 51.6K-parameter tied model reaches the same observed accuracy as the\n289\t160.9K-parameter untied variant.\n290\t\n291\t\n292\t                                                       5\n293\t\fTable 2: Main Speech Commands results from the local architecture comparison. All numbers are single-seed\n294\ttest accuracies.\n295\t          Model                 Configuration                              Test acc. Params\n296\t          MelCumsumFixed            W=5, 8L, n=80, hop=160, untied, 40ep             97.3    160,892\n297\t          MelCumsumFixedTied        W=10, 8L, n=120, hop=80, 80ep                    97.3     51,612\n298\t          MelCNNMaxPool             hop=160, 40ep                                    97.1     25,628\n299\t          MelCumsumFixedTied        W=5, 8L, n=100, hop=160, 40ep                    97.0     37,012\n300\t          MelCumsumBidirTied        W=10, 8L, n=80, hop=80, 40ep                     96.8     31,612\n301\t          MelCumsumFixedTied        W=10, 8L, n=80, hop=80, 80ep                     96.8     24,812\n302\t\n303\t\n304\t\n305\tTable 3: Front-end comparison. Cumsum spectral front ends provide a streaming acoustic representation\n306\tbefore the sequence model.\n307\t             Model               Front end                                     Test acc.    Params\n308\t             MelCNNMaxPool       FFT + log-mel                                     97.1     25,628\n309\t             CumsumSpecCNN       cumsum, frozen mel phases, log-mag+re+im          95.2     46,828\n310\t             CumsumSpecCNN       cumsum, learned phases, log-mag+re+im             93.9     30,508\n311\t             LearnedSpecCNN      cumsum, learned phases, log-mag                   94.1     25,668\n312\t             RawCNN              raw waveform Conv1d                               91.0     25,228\n313\t\n314\t\n315\t\n316\t4.2   Small Local Windows and Depth Matter\n317\t\n318\tThe final results favor repeated local windows over shallow wide aggregation. For example, W=10 with eight\n319\ttied layers reaches 96.8–97.3% depending on width and training length, making repeated tight windows the\n320\tstrongest configuration in the local sweep. Table 7 gives the fixed-model ablation behind this claim: at\n321\ta comparable 40-frame nominal span, moving from two W=20 layers to eight W=5 layers improves test\n322\taccuracy from 94.4% to 96.2%. This supports the interpretation that cumsum is best used as a local temporal\n323\tbuilding block with nonlinear gating between layers, rather than as one large undifferentiated accumulator.\n324\t\n325\t\n326\t4.3   Tying Preserves Performance\n327\t\n328\tThe tied variants are important because they separate architectural structure from raw parameter count.\n329\tThe untied W=5, eight-layer model reaches 97.3% with 160.9K parameters. A tied W=10, eight-layer model\n330\twith n=120 reaches the same 97.3% test accuracy with 51.6K parameters, a reduction of about 3.1x. At\n331\tnearly the same parameter count as the MelCNNMaxPool baseline, the tied W=10, n=80 model reaches\n332\t96.8% with 24.8K parameters. This suggests that repeated local transport with shared projections is a\n333\tcompact temporal mixer rather than merely a larger alternative to convolution.\n334\t\n335\t\n336\t4.4   Cumsum Acoustic Front Ends\n337\t\n338\tReplacing the FFT/mel front end with sinusoidal cumsum filters gives a direct streaming acoustic front end.\n339\tTable 3 shows representative results with the same CNN backend used for the mel reference.\n340\tThe cumsum front end is important because it shows that the same prefix-sum primitive can act before the\n341\tmel stage as well as after it. The strongest cumsum front end uses mel-spaced frozen phases and keeps phase-\n342\tcarrying features, reaching 95.2% before the sequence model. The detailed ablation in tables 11 and 12 shows\n343\tthat retaining real and imaginary channels is especially helpful when the hop is large. On short commands,\n344\tthe fixed FFT/mel/log pipeline still supplies a strong inductive bias. The strongest architecture in this draft\n345\ttherefore uses cumsum transport after mel features, rather than replacing mel features entirely.\n346\t\n347\t\n348\t                                                      6\n349\t\fTable 4: Matched cumsum-versus-scan benchmark. Both models use the same mel front end and tied eight-\n350\tlayer architecture.\n351\t        Model              Temporal primitive                  Params    Best val   Test    B=1 latency\n352\t        MelCumsumFixed     cumsum + hard window W = 10          24,812       94.8   94.82       5.01 ms\n353\t        MelScanFixed       Triton scan + learned decay          25,132       94.2   94.33       7.09 ms\n354\t\n355\t\n356\t         Table 5: Primitive timing at the mel-layer sequence size, T = 200, N = 40, on a Tesla T4.\n357\t                                Batch    torch.cumsum      Triton scan   Ratio\n358\t                                     1           84.9 us      270.6 us    3.2x\n359\t                                     8           84.9 us      273.6 us    3.2x\n360\t                                    32           73.4 us      331.8 us    4.5x\n361\t                                   128          140.5 us      514.5 us    3.7x\n362\t\n363\t\n364\t4.5   Cumsum Versus Learned-Decay Scan\n365\t\n366\tThe most direct systems comparison keeps the mel front end and model shape fixed. Both models use 40-bin\n367\tlog-mel frames at hop 80, d = 80, eight tied layers, the same projections, BatchNorm, GLU residual updates,\n368\tand max-pooling readout. The only substantive difference is the temporal primitive: MelCumsumFixed uses\n369\ta hard window W = 10 implemented by torch.cumsum and prefix subtraction, while MelScanFixed replaces\n370\tthe window with learned per-channel exponential decay implemented by a custom Triton scan. The scan\n371\tmodel has 320 extra parameters, one decay scalar per frequency per layer.\n372\tTable 4 shows comparable accuracy in this single matched run. The primary difference is implementation\n373\tcost: the cumsum model uses ordinary cumulative sums and prefix subtraction, trains in 16.2 seconds per\n374\tepoch versus 17.4 seconds per epoch, and has 1.42x lower single-example inference latency. The raw primitive\n375\tbenchmark gives the cleaner implementation signal. At the mel-layer size T = 200, N = 40, torch.cumsum\n376\tis 3.2–4.5x faster than the Triton scan across batch sizes 1–128.\n377\tThe scan model learns short effective memories. Across layers, the learned decay values imply effective\n378\twindows between roughly 3 and 21 frames. This supports the finite-memory hypothesis: for this keyword-\n379\tspotting configuration, the learned recurrent memory behaves like a short local filter, which the cumsum\n380\twindow supplies directly.\n381\t\n382\t4.6   Streaming Front-End Timing\n383\t\n384\tThe cumsum acoustic front end is also sensitive to implementation details. The initial raw-audio cumsum\n385\tfront end used a strided time dimension and performed window subtraction before downsampling, which\n386\tmade torch.cumsum the bottleneck. Using a contiguous (B, N, T ) layout and indexing stride positions\n387\tbefore downstream operations changes the layer-1 single-example latency from 5.8 ms to 284 us. After these\n388\toptimizations, the cumsum front end matches the mel front end at batch size one: 337 us for the cumsum\n389\tfront end versus 359 us for FFT+log+embedding. At large training batches, the cumsum front end remains\n390\tmemory heavier because it materializes the full-resolution complex rotation tensor; fusing rotation, cumsum,\n391\twindow subtraction, and striding is the natural next implementation step.\n392\t\n393\t5     Discussion\n394\t\n395\tWhat the results support. The reliable finding is that cumsum-composable local transport is a simple\n396\tand effective temporal aggregation layer for keyword spotting. It works best after a mel front end, with\n397\tsmall windows, multiple layers, gating, and weight tying. It has an exact streaming update and a simple\n398\tbatched implementation. The matched scan benchmark supports the systems argument: when the learned\n399\tscan converges to short effective memories, the hard-window cumsum version has similar accuracy and lower\n400\tlatency in the measured setup. This is a useful combination for low-cost streaming speech research.\n401\t\n402\t\n403\t                                                       7\n404\t\f    Table 6: Positioning of cumsum phase transport relative to common streaming sequence model families.\n405\t    Model family         Memory assumption               Training primitive               Streaming form\n406\t    CNN/TCN              finite local receptive field    convolution                      causal buffer\n407\t    S4/S5                long or decaying linear state   scan or structured convolution   recurrence\n408\t    Mamba                input-selective state           selective scan                   recurrence\n409\t    This work            finite unitary transport        cumulative sum and prefix dif-   prefix state, ring buffer\n410\t                                                         ferences\n411\t\n412\t\n413\tRelation to SSMs. SSMs remain natural for long-context streaming models and production voice systems.\n414\tFinite-window speech tasks expose a complementary regime. When the relevant memory is local and the\n415\ttransport operators are rotations, cumulative sums can recover the useful prefix/window structure without\n416\tthe full machinery of selective scan. The closest SSM relatives are diagonal complex models, which also use\n417\tper-channel complex dynamics to generate sequence kernels (Gupta et al., 2022; Gu et al., 2022b; Smith et al.,\n418\t2023). This work restricts the transport to unit-modulus rotations and supplies memory length explicitly\n419\tthrough prefix differences, so the inverse transport used inside the accumulator remains bounded.\n420\t\n421\tScope. The experiments focus on keyword spotting. The next step is to measure whether the same cumsum\n422\ttransport layer retains its cost and latency advantages under stronger baselines, replicated runs, additional\n423\thardware, and streaming trigger metrics used in mobile KWS evaluation (Rybakov et al., 2020; Jose et al.,\n424\t2022).\n425\t\n426\t6     Limitations and Next Experiments\n427\t\n428\tThe current draft has several important limitations. All reported results are single-seed. The SSM compar-\n429\tisons use local research implementations. The current systems benchmark is limited to one GPU environment\n430\tand one matched architecture. Speech Commands is a keyword-spotting benchmark. A fuller perturbation\n431\tsuite would add pitch shift, reverberation, codec distortion, speaker holdout, and event-triggered onset met-\n432\trics.\n433\tThe immediate next experiments are:\n434\t\n435\t1. Replicate the best fixed tied mel+cumsum and MelCNNMaxPool runs over at least three seeds.\n436\t2. Extend wall-clock, memory, throughput, and profiler logging to CPU, Apple Silicon, and embed-\n437\t   ded/mobile targets.\n438\t3. Compare against standard optimized KWS baselines such as DS-CNN, TC-ResNet, BC-ResNet,\n439\t   CRNN/TCN, and small Conformer variants.\n440\t4. Separate three families cleanly: mel+cumsum, learned spectral cumsum, and raw/sample-clocked cum-\n441\t   sum.\n442\t5. Add event-triggered command onset detection so the model is tested on latency and sparse emissions as\n443\t   well as clip-level accuracy.\n444\t6. Expand perturbation tests to pitch shift, reverberation, background noise, codec artifacts, speaker hold-\n445\t   out, and controlled phase/magnitude perturbations.\n446\t\n447\t7     Conclusion\n448\t\n449\tCumsum-composable phase transport gives a simple way to build finite-window streaming speech represen-\n450\ttations with exact batched training and exact online updates. On the local Speech Commands experiments,\n451\tthe strongest evidence supports fixed-frequency mel+cumsum models: they are competitive with the local\n452\tcompact CNN baseline, benefit from small local windows and depth, and retain strong performance under\n453\t\n454\t\n455\t                                                         8\n456\t\fparameter tying. The matched benchmark against a learned-decay scan strengthens the systems claim: in\n457\tthe short-memory regime observed here, the cumsum layer is simpler and lower-latency while retaining com-\n458\tparable accuracy. This makes the next research question concrete: can the cumsum transport layer retain\n459\tits simplicity, cost advantages, and competitive accuracy under multi-seed evaluation, optimized baselines,\n460\tbroader hardware, and harder acoustic distribution shifts?\n461\t\n462\t\n463\t\n464\t\n465\t                                                    9\n466\t\fA     Additional Ablations\n467\t\n468\tThe appendix reports additional ablations from the local experiment notes. All entries are single-seed Speech\n469\tCommands v2 results under the same general training setup described in the main text. The first tables focus\n470\ton the simple fixed mel+cumsum architecture; the final tables summarize the cumsum acoustic front-end\n471\tsweep.\n472\t\n473\tA.1   Window Size and Depth\n474\t\n475\tTable 7 decomposes the tied fixed model by local window size and depth. The main pattern is that a stack\n476\tof small windows is stronger than a shallow model with a wider window. This is consistent with the intended\n477\tuse of the cumsum layer as a local aggregation primitive followed by nonlinear gating.\n478\t\n479\t\n480\tTable 7: Fixed tied mel+cumsum window/depth ablation. The nominal span is L × W in mel frames and is\n481\tused only as a rough comparison of temporal coverage.\n482\t                       Configuration   Nominal span     Layers    Params     Best val      Test\n483\t                       W=20, 2L                  40           2   23,612          94.6      94.4\n484\t                       W=10, 4L                  40           4   24,012          95.7      95.8\n485\t                       W=5, 8L                   40           8   24,812          96.3      96.2\n486\t                       W=20, 4L                  80           4   24,012          94.9      95.2\n487\t                       W=20, 8L                 160           8   24,812          95.0      95.5\n488\t\n489\t\n490\tA.2   Weight Tying\n491\t\n492\tTable 8 isolates the effect of sharing the value projection and GLU across cumsum layers. The tied model\n493\tkeeps per-layer frequencies and normalization, reducing parameters by about 3.4x in this setting while staying\n494\tclose to the untied model and the compact CNN reference.\n495\t\n496\t\n497\t              Table 8: Fixed mel+cumsum weight-tying ablation for W=20, 4-layer models.\n498\t                            Model                            Params   Best val    Test\n499\t                            MelCumsumFixed, untied           82,252        96.0   96.3\n500\t                            MelCumsumFixedTied               24,012        94.9   95.2\n501\t                            MelCNNMaxPool reference          25,628        95.4   95.4\n502\t\n503\t\n504\tA.3   Fixed-Frequency Sweep\n505\t\n506\tTable 9 lists representative fixed-frequency mel+cumsum variants from the later local architecture sweep.\n507\tThe best tied model reaches the same 97.3% test accuracy as the larger untied model at a substantially\n508\tsmaller parameter count.\n509\t\n510\t\n511\t                        Table 9: Representative fixed-frequency mel+cumsum sweep.\n512\t               Model                    Configuration                                Test       Params\n513\t               MelCumsumFixed           W=5, 8L, n=80, hop=160, 40ep, untied             97.3   160,892\n514\t               MelCumsumFixedTied       W=10, 8L, n=120, hop=80, 80ep                    97.3    51,612\n515\t               MelCumsumFixedTied       W=5, 8L, n=100, hop=160, 40ep                    97.0    37,012\n516\t               MelCumsumBidirTied       W=10, 8L, n=80, hop=80, 40ep                     96.8    31,612\n517\t               MelCumsumFixedTied       W=10, 8L, n=80, hop=80, 80ep                     96.8    24,812\n518\t               MelCumsumFixedTied       W=10, 8L, n=80, hop=80, 40ep                     96.5    24,812\n519\t               MelCumsumFixedTied       W=5, 8L, n=80, hop=160, 40ep                     96.2    24,812\n520\t               MelCumsumFixedTied       W=40, 2L, n=80, hop=80, 80ep                     94.5    23,612\n521\t\n522\t\n523\t\n524\t                                                        10\n525\t\fA.4   Architecture Alternatives\n526\t\n527\tTable 10 summarizes additional architecture variants from the same local sweep. These runs address a\n528\tnatural reviewer question: whether the gain is simply from stacking many small nonlinear stages or from a\n529\tmore generic progressive architecture. The tied fixed cumsum model with constant width remains stronger\n530\tthan the progressive cumsum-ResNet variants at similar parameter counts. The comparison places the main\n531\tmodel against nearby compact cumsum architectures and helps separate the fixed phase-transport design\n532\tfrom generic compact cumsum variants.\n533\t\n534\t\n535\t                  Table 10: Architecture alternatives from the local mel+cumsum sweep.\n536\t                Model                       Configuration                        Test      Params\n537\t                MelCNNMaxPool               hop=160, 40ep                        97.1      25,628\n538\t                MelCumsumFixedTied          W=10, 8L, n=80, hop=80, 80ep         96.8      24,812\n539\t                MelCumsumFixedTied          W=5, 8L, n=80, hop=160, 40ep         96.2      24,812\n540\t                MelCumsumResNet             W=3, channels [24,24,32,48], 40ep    94.9      25,380\n541\t                MelCumsumResNet             W=3, channels [16,24,32,48], 40ep    94.6      22,852\n542\t                MelCumsumMagDeepTied        W=5, 8L, n=90, 40ep                  93.0      25,032\n543\t\n544\t\n545\t\n546\tA.5   Cumsum Acoustic Front End\n547\t\n548\tThe main paper uses log-mel features because they remain the strongest acoustic representation in the current\n549\texperiments. The cumsum front-end experiments test a separate question: whether the same prefix-sum\n550\tmechanism can replace the FFT/mel front end while preserving streaming computation from raw audio.\n551\tThe front end maintains running complex sinusoidal sums over waveform samples and emits either log\n552\tmagnitude alone or log magnitude together with the real and imaginary channels.\n553\tTable 11 summarizes the standard 10 ms hop setting. The strongest cumsum front end uses frozen mel-\n554\tspaced phases and a learned linear bottleneck from [log |c|, Re c, Im c] to the CNN input channels. This\n555\treaches 95.2% test accuracy. Within the cumsum front-end family, frozen mel-spaced phases outperform\n556\tlearned phases in this sweep, and retaining phase-carrying real and imaginary channels improves over log\n557\tmagnitude alone.\n558\t\n559\t\n560\tTable 11: Cumsum front-end ablation at hop 160 samples. All rows use 80 acoustic channels and the same\n561\tCNN backend.\n562\t                Model                          Front-end features      Window   Best val     Test\n563\t                MelCNNMaxPool                  FFT + log-mel              400      96.4      97.1\n564\t                CumsumSpec, frozen phases      [log |c|, Re c, Im c]      400      95.2      95.2\n565\t                CumsumSpec, frozen phases      [log |c|, Re c, Im c]      160      95.2      94.8\n566\t                CumsumSpec, learned phases     [log |c|, Re c, Im c]      400      94.0      93.9\n567\t                LearnedSpecCNN                 log |c|                    400         –      93.4\n568\t\n569\t\n570\tTable 12 repeats the comparison in a no-overlap hop-400 setting. This setting makes the phase channels\n571\tmore visible: with learned phases, adding real and imaginary channels raises test accuracy from 90.8% to\n572\t93.6%; with frozen phases, it raises test accuracy from 92.0% to 94.0%.\n573\tTable 13 adds a related learned-filterbank diagnostic. The convolutional sin-cos filterbank uses Hann-\n574\twindowed filters rather than a running rectangular cumsum window. The strongest configuration in this\n575\tsweep is the frozen mel-spaced log-magnitude filterbank. This contrasts with the cumsum front end in ta-\n576\tble 12, where real and imaginary channels help because the running cumsum magnitude is a noisier spectral\n577\testimate.\n578\tTable 14 reports the corresponding end-to-end cumsum sequence models that replace both the acoustic front\n579\tend and the temporal backend with cumsum layers. The same pattern appears there: log magnitude is\n580\t\n581\t\n582\t                                                      11\n583\t\fTable 12: Cumsum front-end ablation at hop 400 samples, where adjacent acoustic frames do not overlap.\n584\t                    Model               Front-end features             Phases    Best val    Test\n585\t                    MelCNNMaxPool       FFT + log-mel               fixed mel        95.3     95.4\n586\t                    CumsumSpec          [log |c|, Re c, Im c]     frozen mel         94.1     94.0\n587\t                    CumsumSpec          [log |c|, Re c, Im c]         learned        94.0     93.6\n588\t                    CumsumSpec          log |c|                   frozen mel         92.7     92.0\n589\t                    CumsumSpec          log |c|                       learned        92.2     90.8\n590\t\n591\t\n592\tTable 13: Sin-cos convolutional filterbank front-end ablation at hop 160 samples. All rows use the same\n593\tCNN backend.\n594\t       Model                                Front-end features                                    Test      Params\n595\t                                                    2         2\n596\t       FilterbankSinCos Frozen              log(sin + cos ), frozen mel filters                      95.7   25,628\n597\t       FilterbankSinCosMagReIm Frozen       [log |c|, sin, cos] → Linear, frozen mel filters         95.4   30,468\n598\t       FilterbankSinCos Learned             log(sin2 + cos2 ), learned filters                       94.7   57,628\n599\t       FilterbankSinCosCombined Learned     [log |c|, sin, cos], learned filters                     94.5   61,468\n600\t\n601\t\n602\ta useful anchor, while carrying real and imaginary channels gives the next layer access to within-window\n603\tphase.\n604\t\n605\t\n606\tTable 14: Mag+re+im ablation for raw-audio cumsum stacks. These models use cumsum front ends followed\n607\tby cumsum temporal layers.\n608\t               Model             Test     Params        Feature path\n609\t               CumsumE2EMag      93.5     62,732        mag+log front end; complex cumsum layers\n610\t               MagDeep V2        92.8     71,556        [log |c|, Re c, Im c] all layers, with projection\n611\t               MagDeep V2        92.5     63,812        log-mag first layer, then [log |c|, Re c, Im c]\n612\t               MagDeep V1        90.5     65,084        log-mag only, wider model\n613\t               MagDeep V1        89.2     33,692        log-mag only, smaller model\n614\t\n615\t\n616\t\n617\tReferences\n618\tGuy E. Blelloch. Prefix sums and their applications. Technical Report CMU-CS-90-190, School of Computer\n619\t Science, Carnegie Mellon University, 1990.\n620\t\n621\tSeungwoo Choi, Seokjun Seo, Beomjun Shin, Hyeongmin Byun, Martin Kersner, Beomsu Kim, Dongyoung\n622\t  Kim, and Sungjoo Ha. Temporal Convolution for Real-time Keyword Spotting on Mobile Devices. In\n623\t  Proc. Interspeech 2019, pp. 3372–3376, 2019. doi: 10.21437/Interspeech.2019-1363.\n624\t\n625\tAlbert Gu and Tri Dao. Mamba: Linear-time sequence modeling with selective state spaces. arXiv preprint\n626\t  arXiv:2312.00752, 2023.\n627\t\n628\tAlbert Gu, Karan Goel, and Christopher Ré. Efficiently modeling long sequences with structured state\n629\t  spaces. In Proc. International Conference on Learning Representations, 2022a.\n630\t\n631\tAlbert Gu, Ankit Gupta, Karan Goel, and Christopher Ré. On the parameterization and initialization of\n632\t  diagonal state space models. arXiv preprint arXiv:2206.11893, 2022b.\n633\t\n634\tAnkit Gupta, Albert Gu, and Jonathan Berant. Diagonal state spaces are as effective as structured state\n635\t spaces. In Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems, volume 35, 2022.\n636\t\n637\tChristin Jose, Joe Wang, Grant Strimel, Mohammad Omar Khursheed, Yuriy Mishchenko, and Brian Kulis.\n638\t  Latency Control for Keyword Spotting. In Proc. Interspeech 2022, pp. 1891–1895, 2022. doi: 10.21437/\n639\t  Interspeech.2022-10608.\n640\t\n641\t\n642\t                                                         12\n643\t\fByeonggeun Kim, Simyung Chang, Jinkyu Lee, and Dooyong Sung. Broadcasted Residual Learning for\n644\t  Efficient Keyword Spotting. In Proc. Interspeech 2021, pp. 4538–4542, 2021. doi: 10.21437/Interspeech.\n645\t  2021-383.\n646\tDaniel S Park, William Chan, Yu Zhang, Chung-Cheng Chiu, Barret Zoph, Ekin D Cubuk, and Quoc V Le.\n647\t SpecAugment: A simple data augmentation method for automatic speech recognition. In Proc. Interspeech\n648\t 2019, pp. 2613–2617, 2019. doi: 10.21437/Interspeech.2019-2680.\n649\t\n650\tOleg Rybakov, Natasha Kononenko, Niranjan Subrahmanya, Mirkó Visontai, and Stella Laurenzo. Streaming\n651\t  Keyword Spotting on Mobile Devices. In Proc. Interspeech 2020, pp. 2277–2281, 2020. doi: 10.21437/\n652\t  Interspeech.2020-1003.\n653\tJimmy T. H. Smith, Andrew Warrington, and Scott W. Linderman. Simplified state space layers for sequence\n654\t  modeling. In Proc. International Conference on Learning Representations, 2023.\n655\t\n656\tJianlin Su, Yu Lu, Shengfeng Pan, Ahmed Murtadha, Bo Wen, and Yunfeng Liu. RoFormer: Enhanced\n657\t  transformer with rotary position embedding. arXiv preprint arXiv:2104.09864, 2021.\n658\tAshish Vaswani, Noam Shazeer, Niki Parmar, Jakob Uszkoreit, Llion Jones, Aidan N Gomez, Lukasz Kaiser,\n659\t  and Illia Polosukhin. Attention is all you need. In Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems,\n660\t  volume 30, 2017.\n661\tPete Warden. Speech commands: A dataset for limited-vocabulary speech recognition. arXiv preprint\n662\t  arXiv:1804.03209, 2018.\n663\tNeil Zeghidour, Olivier Teboul, Félix de Chaumont Quitry, and Marco Tagliasacchi. LEAF: A learnable\n664\t  frontend for audio classification. In Proc. International Conference on Learning Representations, 2021.\n665\t\n666\tYundong Zhang, Naveen Suda, Liangzhen Lai, and Vikas Chandra. Hello edge: Keyword spotting on\n667\t  microcontrollers. In Proceedings of Machine Learning and Systems, 2018.\n668\t\n669\t\n670\t\n671\t\n672\t                                                   13\n673\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "e9da1eea-35c7-4bce-a0bf-64def6bf7411", "uuid": "292a6bb6-67dc-427b-83af-41737048e069", "timestamp": "2026-07-23T08:09:01.036Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/arxiv_2607.20086.txt", "content": "                                         Cumsum-Composable Phase Transport\n                                         for Low-Cost Streaming Keyword Spotting\n\n                                         Mahesh Godavarti\n                                         A Carrot, Inc\n\n\n\n                                                                                            Abstract\n\n                                                 State-space sequence models are attractive for streaming speech because they carry a com-\n                                                 pact state through time, but their training cost can depend on scan-style kernels whose\n                                                 constant factors are unfavorable for short audio tasks and commodity GPUs. We study\n                                                 a simpler streaming-native alternative for keyword spotting: phase-transport layers whose\n                                                 products reduce to cumulative sums. Each layer maps frame features to complex channels,\n                                                 transports them by learned rotations, accumulates over a finite window by prefix differences,\n                                                 and then applies a gated residual update. The same representation has an exact batched\narXiv:2607.20086v1 [cs.SD] 22 Jul 2026\n\n\n\n\n                                                 training form and an exact online inference form: batch training uses ordinary cumulative\n                                                 sums, while streaming inference maintains the same prefix state with one update per frame\n                                                 and recovers rolling windows by prefix differences. The key structural assumption is unitary\n                                                 transport: inverse rotations used to build the prefix state are norm-preserving, so finite\n                                                 memory is introduced by window or block readouts rather than by ill-conditioned inverse\n                                                 decay factors.\n                                                 On Google Speech Commands v2 with 12 labels, mel+cumsum models are competitive with\n                                                 our compact convolutional baseline. The strongest single-seed mel+cumsum run reaches\n                                                 97.3% test accuracy; a 51.6K-parameter tied variant reaches the same value, and a 24.8K-\n                                                 parameter tied model reaches 96.8%, comparable to a 25.6K-parameter MelCNNMaxPool\n                                                 baseline at 97.1%. In a matched cumsum-versus-scan benchmark with the same mel front\n                                                 end, tied projections, normalization, and gating, cumsum+window gives comparable test\n                                                 accuracy, 94.82% versus 94.33% for a learned-decay scan, while training 1.07x faster and\n                                                 reducing single-example latency from 7.09 ms to 5.01 ms on a Tesla T4. An optimized raw-\n                                                 audio cumsum front end matches mel front-end single-example latency in this setup, 337\n                                                 microseconds versus 359 microseconds. Overall, cumsum-composable local transport retains\n                                                 competitive keyword-spotting accuracy while replacing scan-style temporal aggregation with\n                                                 ordinary cumulative sums, prefix differences, and a small streaming state.\n\n\n                                         1   Introduction\n                                         Streaming speech systems need to preserve temporal evidence while processing audio under tight latency\n                                         and cost constraints. Modern state-space models (SSMs) are one answer: they replace all-pairs attention\n                                         over long histories with a compact recurrent state, and selective variants can choose what to retain or forget\n                                         as input arrives (Gu et al., 2022a; Smith et al., 2023; Gu & Dao, 2023). For short-window keyword spotting,\n                                         however, the practical tradeoff is different. A one-second command is a finite local pattern, and compact\n                                         CNNs already map well to commodity hardware (Zhang et al., 2018; Choi et al., 2019; Kim et al., 2021). If an\n                                         SSM-like model requires scan kernels, repeated state updates, and nontrivial backward passes, its asymptotic\n                                         linearity may not translate into low training cost on small tasks.\n                                         This paper studies a cumsum-composable alternative. The central operation is a transported finite-window\n                                         sum. Given complex value channels zt ∈ Cn and phase operators Ut = diag(eiϕt,1 , . . . , eiϕt,n ), define\n                                                                                                t\n                                                                                                X\n                                                                                yt = Ut                      Uτ−1 zτ .                              (1)\n                                                                                          τ =max(1,t−W +1)\n\n\n                                                                                                 1\n\fThis is a local phase-transport analogue of a recurrent memory: evidence from time τ is carried into the\ncoordinate frame at time t before aggregation. When the phases are fixed or are cumulative sums of per-\nframe increments, eq. (1) is computed by prefix sums and prefix differences, one of the standard primitives\nfor parallel sequence computation (Blelloch, 1990). It is therefore easy to train in parallel and easy to run in\nstreaming mode. The transport makes this more expressive than an ordinary cumulative sum over frames.\nThe contribution of frame τ to output time t is Ut Uτ−1 zτ , so the layer computes learned relative-phase\nevidence as a function of lag while still admitting a prefix representation.\nThe experiments in this paper are deliberately modest. We use Google Speech Commands v2 (Warden,\n2018), a short-command benchmark, to ask whether this architecture is worth studying before scaling to\nfull ASR. Fixed-frequency mel+cumsum models are strong and efficient. The contribution is a practical\narchitectural result: finite-memory unitary transport gives a useful class of streaming sequence layers whose\nrecurrence factors exactly into prefix accumulators. The experiments show that this simpler batch and\nstreaming implementation remains accurate enough to be viable on this task.\n\nContributions.     We make six claims, all scoped to the local experiments reported here.\n\n• We formulate a phase-transport layer whose finite-window representation is computed by cumulative sums\n  and has an exact streaming equivalent.\n• We explain why unitary transport is the structural assumption that makes the prefix factorization nu-\n  merically well conditioned: the inverse transports remain bounded.\n• We describe the corresponding streaming front end: audio is converted to low-latency mel or learned\n  spectral frames, each frame updates the cumsum state once, and rolling keyword scores are emitted from\n  finite-window states.\n• We show that stacked local mel+cumsum layers are competitive with the compact CNN baseline in our\n  local Speech Commands setup, reaching up to 97.3% test accuracy.\n• We show that tied local cumsum layers retain strong accuracy with small parameter counts, including a\n  24.8K-parameter model at 96.8%.\n• We report a matched systems benchmark against a learned-decay scan layer, showing lower latency and\n  comparable accuracy without a custom scan kernel.\n\n2     Cumsum Phase Transport\n2.1    Windowed Transport by Prefix Differences\n\nLet zt ∈ Cn be the complex value produced from an input feature vector at time t. Let Ut ∈ Cn×n be a\ndiagonal unitary transport operator. The transported finite-window sum in eq. (1) can be written with a\nprefix accumulator\n                                                 Xt\n                                            pt =    Uτ−1 zτ .                                       (2)\n                                                     τ =1\nThen\n                                  yt = Ut (pt − pt−W ) ,    ps = 0 for s ≤ 0.                               (3)\nThis is the entire computational advantage: the layer uses a cumulative sum of transported values, a delayed\nprefix subtraction, and an elementwise rotation back to the current frame.\nProposition 1 (Exact batch/streaming equivalence). For fixed model parameters and a fixed input sequence,\neq. (3) produces the same yt whether pt is computed by a batched cumulative sum over the whole sequence or\nby the streaming update\n                                             pt = pt−1 + Ut−1 zt .\n                                                      Pt\nProof. The streaming recurrence expands to pt = τ =1 Uτ−1 zτ , which is exactly the batched cumulative\nsum. Substituting this prefix into eq. (3) gives the same finite-window transported sum.\n\n\n                                                       2\n\f2.2   Why Transport Before Accumulation?\n\nAn ordinary cumulative sum aggregates values in a fixed coordinate system. Temporal order enters only\nthrough window membership and through nonlinear layers after the sum. Phase transport changes the\noperation: the contribution from time τ to time t is\n\n                                                   Ut Uτ−1 zτ .\n\nFor fixed learned phases ϕt,k = tωk , the kth complex coordinate is weighted by ei(t−τ )ωk . The layer therefore\nimplements learned oscillatory kernels over relative lag, but all such kernels share a cumsum implementation\nbecause each term can be moved into a common prefix coordinate system before accumulation. This is\nthe modeling role of complex rotations: they make the accumulated evidence depend on relative phase,\nnot only on the unordered sum of local values. Complex exponentials and rotations are standard tools in\nsequence models, appearing in sinusoidal and rotary position representations as well as diagonal complex\nstate-space parameterizations (Vaswani et al., 2017; Su et al., 2021; Gupta et al., 2022; Gu et al., 2022b). The\ncontribution here is narrower: a finite-window, unitary transport parameterization whose online recurrence\nand batched training computation are exactly the same prefix representation.\n\n2.3   Streaming Front End\n\nThe cumsum layer is naturally paired with a streaming acoustic front end. At deployment, incoming wave-\nform samples are held in a short analysis buffer. Every hop, for example 80 samples (5 ms) or 160 samples\n(10 ms) at 16 kHz, the front end emits one acoustic frame. That frame can be a conventional log-mel vec-\ntor, as in the strongest experiments here, or a learned cumsum spectral vector as in the learned-front-end\nexperiments.\nThe online pipeline is:\n\n                  x1:t → mt → zt → pt = pt−1 + Ut−1 zt → yt = Ut (pt − pt−W ) → st .\n\nHere mt is the acoustic frame, zt is the complex value injected into the transport layer, pt is the maintained\nprefix state, yt is the current finite-window transported state, and st is a keyword logit or trigger score. The\nmodel therefore does not need to wait for a full one-second clip. It can update a rolling score at the frame hop\nrate and emit when the score crosses a task-specific threshold. Continuous-stream keyword spotting normally\nrequires additional trigger metrics such as false accepts, false rejects, and detection latency (Rybakov et al.,\n2020; Jose et al., 2022); the present experiments evaluate the model first as a clip classifier with an exact\nstreaming implementation. Figure 1 summarizes the resulting streaming layer.\nThe memory needed per layer is small. For a hard window, the implementation stores the current prefix pt\nand a ring buffer of old prefixes needed to form pt − pt−W . For block decay, it stores block summaries and\nupdates them at block boundaries. In both cases, online inference uses the same representation as batched\ntraining; the difference is only whether prefixes are produced by a full-sequence cumulative sum or by the\none-frame recurrence.\n\n2.4   Fixed Learned Phases\n\nThe fixed-frequency models use one learned frequency per complex channel and layer:\n\n                                                  ϕt,k = tωk .                                              (4)\n\nThis gives each complex channel a learned local oscillator. The resulting rotations are unitary, so the\ntransport part is norm-preserving; finite memory is supplied by the window or block-decay readout rather\nthan by continuously damping the oscillator. Because the phases are deterministic functions of time within\na layer, the whole sequence can be processed by cumulative sums during training and by a one-step prefix\nupdate during streaming inference.\n\n\n                                                        3\n\fTable 1: Simple fixed mel+cumsum architecture. The main experiments vary d, L, W , hop length, and\nwhether the projection/GLU are tied across layers.\n      Component                Implementation\n      Acoustic front end       40-bin log-mel spectrogram, 16 kHz audio, 400-sample FFT window, hop 80 or\n                               160 samples; SpecAugment during training.\n      Embedding                Linear map mt ∈ R40 to ht ∈ Rd .\n      Value projection         Linear map ht 7→ (at , bt ) ∈ Rd/2 × Rd/2 , interpreted as zt = at + ibt .\n      Fixed phase bank         Per-layer learned\n                                              P frequencies   ωℓ,k with ϕt,k = tωℓ,k and Ut = diag(eiϕt,k ).\n                                                       −1\n      Cumsum transport         Compute pt = τ ≤t Uτ zτ and read out yt = Ut (pt − pt−W ).\n      Layer update             Concatenate [ℜyt , ℑyt ], apply BatchNorm, GLU, and residual addition.\n      Classifier               Convert final real/imaginary channels to magnitudes, max-pool over time, and\n                               apply a linear 12-way classifier.\n      Tied variant             Share the value projection and GLU across all layers; keep frequencies and\n                               BatchNorm separate per layer.\n\n\n2.5    Why Unitary Transport?\n\nThe prefix construction requires applying an inverse transport to each incoming value before accumulation.\nFor unitary rotations, Ut−1 = Ut∗ and ∥Ut−1 z∥ = ∥z∥, so the prefix terms remain on the same numerical scale\nas the projected values. This is the algebraic reason that batch cumsums and streaming prefix updates are\nboth simple and stable.\nThe contrast with decaying transport clarifies the design choice. Suppose one tried to use At = ρt Ut\nwith 0 < ρ < 1 in the same prefix form. The prefix accumulator would contain terms A−1       τ zτ = ρ     Uτ zτ .\n                                                                                                       −τ −1\n\nAlthough the final readout could multiply by a small forward factor and cancel this scaling in exact arithmetic,\nthe prefix state itself would involve division by progressively smaller numbers. In finite precision this can\ncreate large scale separation, overflow risk, and loss of low-order information. Unitary transport avoids this\nclass of conditioning issues because the inverse used to build prefixes has norm one. For this reason, forgetting\nis introduced outside the transport inversion, through hard-window subtraction or block-level weighting.\n\n2.6    Layer Form\n\nThe main mel+cumsum layer follows the implementation in the local experiment code. A log-mel frame\nmt ∈ R40 is embedded into ht ∈ Rd . At each cumsum layer, a linear projection creates real and imaginary\nchannels:\n                                    (at , bt ) = Pℓ ht , zt = at + ibt .\nThe transported window sum yt is computed by eq. (3), converted back to real coordinates, normalized, and\npassed through a gated residual update:\n\n                                       ht ← ht + GLU(BN([ℜyt , ℑyt ])).                                        (5)\n\nFor windowed classification, the model collapses the final complex channels to magnitudes and applies tem-\nporal max pooling. Tied variants share the projection and GLU across layers while retaining per-layer\nfrequency and normalization parameters. Table 1 summarizes the simple fixed-frequency architecture used\nfor the main mel+cumsum results.\n\n2.7    Block Decay\n\nHard finite windows are efficient but can be unstable because the representation changes discontinuously when\nan old term exits the window. The block-decay variant replaces a single hard window with a geometrically\nweighted sum of blocks:\n                                             K−1\n                                              X\n                                     yt = Ut     λb pt−bW − pt−(b+1)W .                                    (6)\n                                                                         \u0001\n\n                                             b=0\n\n\n                                                       4\n\f                       streaming         complex            inverse          prefix\n                       frames mt       projection zt       transport       update pt\n\n\n\n                         rolling        BN + GLU           transport        window\n                        score st         residual          to time t       difference\n\n\nFigure 1: Streaming phase-transport layer. Batch training computes all prefixes by a cumulative sum;\nstreaming inference maintains the same prefix state one frame at a time.\n\n\nThis keeps the computation cumsum-based while adding smooth forgetting. The main mel experiments in\nthis paper use hard windows; block decay is a cumsum-compatible alternative for settings where smoother\nforgetting is useful.\n\n\n3     Experimental Setup\n\nDataset. All experiments use Google Speech Commands v2 with one-second 16 kHz clips. The label set\nhas 12 classes: ten commands (yes, no, up, down, left, right, on, off, stop, go) plus unknown and silence.\nUnknown examples are subsampled to match the average number of target-command examples; silence is\ngenerated from the dataset background-noise clips.\n\nBaselines. We compare three families. First, compact convolutional baselines use either log-mel fea-\ntures or raw waveform convolutions. The strongest mel baseline is MelCNNMaxPool, a TC-ResNet-style\none-dimensional temporal CNN over log-mel channels with SpecAugment (Choi et al., 2019; Park et al.,\n2019). Published KWS systems include DS-CNN-style embedded models and stronger broadcast-residual\nCNNs (Zhang et al., 2018; Kim et al., 2021); the local MelCNNMaxPool model serves as the controlled\ncompact reference for the experiments below. Second, learned spectral front ends replace the fixed FFT/mel\ntransform with learned sinusoidal cumsum filters, connecting this part of the study to learned audio front\nends such as LEAF (Zeghidour et al., 2021). Third, a matched scan baseline keeps the same mel front end,\ntied projections, normalization, and gating as the cumsum model, but replaces each hard-window cumsum\nwith a learned exponential-decay scan.\n\nTraining. Full runs use the full local training set, approximately 36K examples, for 40 or 80 epochs\ndepending on the experiment. Smoke tests use a two-epoch subset of roughly 4K training examples and are\nused only for architectural deconstruction. Mel/CNN models use Adam with learning rate 10−3 and weight\ndecay 10−4 . All reported results in this draft are single-seed unless otherwise stated. The cumsum-versus-\nscan systems benchmark was run on a Tesla T4 with CUDA 12.4, PyTorch 2.6, Torchaudio 2.6, and batch\nsize 128 for training.\n\n\n4     Results\n\n4.1   Mel+Cumsum Is Competitive\n\nTable 2 shows the strongest local mel+cumsum and CNN results. The strongest single-seed cumsum runs\nreach 97.3% test accuracy. A cumsum-composable temporal primitive remains comparable to the local CNN\nbaseline while using an exact streaming prefix representation. Tying and small local windows preserve most\nof the performance with much lower parameter counts.\nThe 24.8K-parameter fixed tied model is the cleanest efficiency result: it is close to the 25.6K-parameter\nMelCNNMaxPool baseline while replacing temporal convolutions after the mel front end with cumsum-\ncomposable phase transport. The 51.6K-parameter tied model reaches the same observed accuracy as the\n160.9K-parameter untied variant.\n\n\n                                                       5\n\fTable 2: Main Speech Commands results from the local architecture comparison. All numbers are single-seed\ntest accuracies.\n          Model                 Configuration                              Test acc. Params\n          MelCumsumFixed            W=5, 8L, n=80, hop=160, untied, 40ep             97.3    160,892\n          MelCumsumFixedTied        W=10, 8L, n=120, hop=80, 80ep                    97.3     51,612\n          MelCNNMaxPool             hop=160, 40ep                                    97.1     25,628\n          MelCumsumFixedTied        W=5, 8L, n=100, hop=160, 40ep                    97.0     37,012\n          MelCumsumBidirTied        W=10, 8L, n=80, hop=80, 40ep                     96.8     31,612\n          MelCumsumFixedTied        W=10, 8L, n=80, hop=80, 80ep                     96.8     24,812\n\n\n\nTable 3: Front-end comparison. Cumsum spectral front ends provide a streaming acoustic representation\nbefore the sequence model.\n             Model               Front end                                     Test acc.    Params\n             MelCNNMaxPool       FFT + log-mel                                     97.1     25,628\n             CumsumSpecCNN       cumsum, frozen mel phases, log-mag+re+im          95.2     46,828\n             CumsumSpecCNN       cumsum, learned phases, log-mag+re+im             93.9     30,508\n             LearnedSpecCNN      cumsum, learned phases, log-mag                   94.1     25,668\n             RawCNN              raw waveform Conv1d                               91.0     25,228\n\n\n\n4.2   Small Local Windows and Depth Matter\n\nThe final results favor repeated local windows over shallow wide aggregation. For example, W=10 with eight\ntied layers reaches 96.8–97.3% depending on width and training length, making repeated tight windows the\nstrongest configuration in the local sweep. Table 7 gives the fixed-model ablation behind this claim: at\na comparable 40-frame nominal span, moving from two W=20 layers to eight W=5 layers improves test\naccuracy from 94.4% to 96.2%. This supports the interpretation that cumsum is best used as a local temporal\nbuilding block with nonlinear gating between layers, rather than as one large undifferentiated accumulator.\n\n\n4.3   Tying Preserves Performance\n\nThe tied variants are important because they separate architectural structure from raw parameter count.\nThe untied W=5, eight-layer model reaches 97.3% with 160.9K parameters. A tied W=10, eight-layer model\nwith n=120 reaches the same 97.3% test accuracy with 51.6K parameters, a reduction of about 3.1x. At\nnearly the same parameter count as the MelCNNMaxPool baseline, the tied W=10, n=80 model reaches\n96.8% with 24.8K parameters. This suggests that repeated local transport with shared projections is a\ncompact temporal mixer rather than merely a larger alternative to convolution.\n\n\n4.4   Cumsum Acoustic Front Ends\n\nReplacing the FFT/mel front end with sinusoidal cumsum filters gives a direct streaming acoustic front end.\nTable 3 shows representative results with the same CNN backend used for the mel reference.\nThe cumsum front end is important because it shows that the same prefix-sum primitive can act before the\nmel stage as well as after it. The strongest cumsum front end uses mel-spaced frozen phases and keeps phase-\ncarrying features, reaching 95.2% before the sequence model. The detailed ablation in tables 11 and 12 shows\nthat retaining real and imaginary channels is especially helpful when the hop is large. On short commands,\nthe fixed FFT/mel/log pipeline still supplies a strong inductive bias. The strongest architecture in this draft\ntherefore uses cumsum transport after mel features, rather than replacing mel features entirely.\n\n\n                                                      6\n\fTable 4: Matched cumsum-versus-scan benchmark. Both models use the same mel front end and tied eight-\nlayer architecture.\n        Model              Temporal primitive                  Params    Best val   Test    B=1 latency\n        MelCumsumFixed     cumsum + hard window W = 10          24,812       94.8   94.82       5.01 ms\n        MelScanFixed       Triton scan + learned decay          25,132       94.2   94.33       7.09 ms\n\n\n         Table 5: Primitive timing at the mel-layer sequence size, T = 200, N = 40, on a Tesla T4.\n                                Batch    torch.cumsum      Triton scan   Ratio\n                                     1           84.9 us      270.6 us    3.2x\n                                     8           84.9 us      273.6 us    3.2x\n                                    32           73.4 us      331.8 us    4.5x\n                                   128          140.5 us      514.5 us    3.7x\n\n\n4.5   Cumsum Versus Learned-Decay Scan\n\nThe most direct systems comparison keeps the mel front end and model shape fixed. Both models use 40-bin\nlog-mel frames at hop 80, d = 80, eight tied layers, the same projections, BatchNorm, GLU residual updates,\nand max-pooling readout. The only substantive difference is the temporal primitive: MelCumsumFixed uses\na hard window W = 10 implemented by torch.cumsum and prefix subtraction, while MelScanFixed replaces\nthe window with learned per-channel exponential decay implemented by a custom Triton scan. The scan\nmodel has 320 extra parameters, one decay scalar per frequency per layer.\nTable 4 shows comparable accuracy in this single matched run. The primary difference is implementation\ncost: the cumsum model uses ordinary cumulative sums and prefix subtraction, trains in 16.2 seconds per\nepoch versus 17.4 seconds per epoch, and has 1.42x lower single-example inference latency. The raw primitive\nbenchmark gives the cleaner implementation signal. At the mel-layer size T = 200, N = 40, torch.cumsum\nis 3.2–4.5x faster than the Triton scan across batch sizes 1–128.\nThe scan model learns short effective memories. Across layers, the learned decay values imply effective\nwindows between roughly 3 and 21 frames. This supports the finite-memory hypothesis: for this keyword-\nspotting configuration, the learned recurrent memory behaves like a short local filter, which the cumsum\nwindow supplies directly.\n\n4.6   Streaming Front-End Timing\n\nThe cumsum acoustic front end is also sensitive to implementation details. The initial raw-audio cumsum\nfront end used a strided time dimension and performed window subtraction before downsampling, which\nmade torch.cumsum the bottleneck. Using a contiguous (B, N, T ) layout and indexing stride positions\nbefore downstream operations changes the layer-1 single-example latency from 5.8 ms to 284 us. After these\noptimizations, the cumsum front end matches the mel front end at batch size one: 337 us for the cumsum\nfront end versus 359 us for FFT+log+embedding. At large training batches, the cumsum front end remains\nmemory heavier because it materializes the full-resolution complex rotation tensor; fusing rotation, cumsum,\nwindow subtraction, and striding is the natural next implementation step.\n\n5     Discussion\n\nWhat the results support. The reliable finding is that cumsum-composable local transport is a simple\nand effective temporal aggregation layer for keyword spotting. It works best after a mel front end, with\nsmall windows, multiple layers, gating, and weight tying. It has an exact streaming update and a simple\nbatched implementation. The matched scan benchmark supports the systems argument: when the learned\nscan converges to short effective memories, the hard-window cumsum version has similar accuracy and lower\nlatency in the measured setup. This is a useful combination for low-cost streaming speech research.\n\n\n                                                       7\n\f    Table 6: Positioning of cumsum phase transport relative to common streaming sequence model families.\n    Model family         Memory assumption               Training primitive               Streaming form\n    CNN/TCN              finite local receptive field    convolution                      causal buffer\n    S4/S5                long or decaying linear state   scan or structured convolution   recurrence\n    Mamba                input-selective state           selective scan                   recurrence\n    This work            finite unitary transport        cumulative sum and prefix dif-   prefix state, ring buffer\n                                                         ferences\n\n\nRelation to SSMs. SSMs remain natural for long-context streaming models and production voice systems.\nFinite-window speech tasks expose a complementary regime. When the relevant memory is local and the\ntransport operators are rotations, cumulative sums can recover the useful prefix/window structure without\nthe full machinery of selective scan. The closest SSM relatives are diagonal complex models, which also use\nper-channel complex dynamics to generate sequence kernels (Gupta et al., 2022; Gu et al., 2022b; Smith et al.,\n2023). This work restricts the transport to unit-modulus rotations and supplies memory length explicitly\nthrough prefix differences, so the inverse transport used inside the accumulator remains bounded.\n\nScope. The experiments focus on keyword spotting. The next step is to measure whether the same cumsum\ntransport layer retains its cost and latency advantages under stronger baselines, replicated runs, additional\nhardware, and streaming trigger metrics used in mobile KWS evaluation (Rybakov et al., 2020; Jose et al.,\n2022).\n\n6     Limitations and Next Experiments\n\nThe current draft has several important limitations. All reported results are single-seed. The SSM compar-\nisons use local research implementations. The current systems benchmark is limited to one GPU environment\nand one matched architecture. Speech Commands is a keyword-spotting benchmark. A fuller perturbation\nsuite would add pitch shift, reverberation, codec distortion, speaker holdout, and event-triggered onset met-\nrics.\nThe immediate next experiments are:\n\n1. Replicate the best fixed tied mel+cumsum and MelCNNMaxPool runs over at least three seeds.\n2. Extend wall-clock, memory, throughput, and profiler logging to CPU, Apple Silicon, and embed-\n   ded/mobile targets.\n3. Compare against standard optimized KWS baselines such as DS-CNN, TC-ResNet, BC-ResNet,\n   CRNN/TCN, and small Conformer variants.\n4. Separate three families cleanly: mel+cumsum, learned spectral cumsum, and raw/sample-clocked cum-\n   sum.\n5. Add event-triggered command onset detection so the model is tested on latency and sparse emissions as\n   well as clip-level accuracy.\n6. Expand perturbation tests to pitch shift, reverberation, background noise, codec artifacts, speaker hold-\n   out, and controlled phase/magnitude perturbations.\n\n7     Conclusion\n\nCumsum-composable phase transport gives a simple way to build finite-window streaming speech represen-\ntations with exact batched training and exact online updates. On the local Speech Commands experiments,\nthe strongest evidence supports fixed-frequency mel+cumsum models: they are competitive with the local\ncompact CNN baseline, benefit from small local windows and depth, and retain strong performance under\n\n\n                                                         8\n\fparameter tying. The matched benchmark against a learned-decay scan strengthens the systems claim: in\nthe short-memory regime observed here, the cumsum layer is simpler and lower-latency while retaining com-\nparable accuracy. This makes the next research question concrete: can the cumsum transport layer retain\nits simplicity, cost advantages, and competitive accuracy under multi-seed evaluation, optimized baselines,\nbroader hardware, and harder acoustic distribution shifts?\n\n\n\n\n                                                    9\n\fA     Additional Ablations\n\nThe appendix reports additional ablations from the local experiment notes. All entries are single-seed Speech\nCommands v2 results under the same general training setup described in the main text. The first tables focus\non the simple fixed mel+cumsum architecture; the final tables summarize the cumsum acoustic front-end\nsweep.\n\nA.1   Window Size and Depth\n\nTable 7 decomposes the tied fixed model by local window size and depth. The main pattern is that a stack\nof small windows is stronger than a shallow model with a wider window. This is consistent with the intended\nuse of the cumsum layer as a local aggregation primitive followed by nonlinear gating.\n\n\nTable 7: Fixed tied mel+cumsum window/depth ablation. The nominal span is L × W in mel frames and is\nused only as a rough comparison of temporal coverage.\n                       Configuration   Nominal span     Layers    Params     Best val      Test\n                       W=20, 2L                  40           2   23,612          94.6      94.4\n                       W=10, 4L                  40           4   24,012          95.7      95.8\n                       W=5, 8L                   40           8   24,812          96.3      96.2\n                       W=20, 4L                  80           4   24,012          94.9      95.2\n                       W=20, 8L                 160           8   24,812          95.0      95.5\n\n\nA.2   Weight Tying\n\nTable 8 isolates the effect of sharing the value projection and GLU across cumsum layers. The tied model\nkeeps per-layer frequencies and normalization, reducing parameters by about 3.4x in this setting while staying\nclose to the untied model and the compact CNN reference.\n\n\n              Table 8: Fixed mel+cumsum weight-tying ablation for W=20, 4-layer models.\n                            Model                            Params   Best val    Test\n                            MelCumsumFixed, untied           82,252        96.0   96.3\n                            MelCumsumFixedTied               24,012        94.9   95.2\n                            MelCNNMaxPool reference          25,628        95.4   95.4\n\n\nA.3   Fixed-Frequency Sweep\n\nTable 9 lists representative fixed-frequency mel+cumsum variants from the later local architecture sweep.\nThe best tied model reaches the same 97.3% test accuracy as the larger untied model at a substantially\nsmaller parameter count.\n\n\n                        Table 9: Representative fixed-frequency mel+cumsum sweep.\n               Model                    Configuration                                Test       Params\n               MelCumsumFixed           W=5, 8L, n=80, hop=160, 40ep, untied             97.3   160,892\n               MelCumsumFixedTied       W=10, 8L, n=120, hop=80, 80ep                    97.3    51,612\n               MelCumsumFixedTied       W=5, 8L, n=100, hop=160, 40ep                    97.0    37,012\n               MelCumsumBidirTied       W=10, 8L, n=80, hop=80, 40ep                     96.8    31,612\n               MelCumsumFixedTied       W=10, 8L, n=80, hop=80, 80ep                     96.8    24,812\n               MelCumsumFixedTied       W=10, 8L, n=80, hop=80, 40ep                     96.5    24,812\n               MelCumsumFixedTied       W=5, 8L, n=80, hop=160, 40ep                     96.2    24,812\n               MelCumsumFixedTied       W=40, 2L, n=80, hop=80, 80ep                     94.5    23,612\n\n\n\n                                                        10\n\fA.4   Architecture Alternatives\n\nTable 10 summarizes additional architecture variants from the same local sweep. These runs address a\nnatural reviewer question: whether the gain is simply from stacking many small nonlinear stages or from a\nmore generic progressive architecture. The tied fixed cumsum model with constant width remains stronger\nthan the progressive cumsum-ResNet variants at similar parameter counts. The comparison places the main\nmodel against nearby compact cumsum architectures and helps separate the fixed phase-transport design\nfrom generic compact cumsum variants.\n\n\n                  Table 10: Architecture alternatives from the local mel+cumsum sweep.\n                Model                       Configuration                        Test      Params\n                MelCNNMaxPool               hop=160, 40ep                        97.1      25,628\n                MelCumsumFixedTied          W=10, 8L, n=80, hop=80, 80ep         96.8      24,812\n                MelCumsumFixedTied          W=5, 8L, n=80, hop=160, 40ep         96.2      24,812\n                MelCumsumResNet             W=3, channels [24,24,32,48], 40ep    94.9      25,380\n                MelCumsumResNet             W=3, channels [16,24,32,48], 40ep    94.6      22,852\n                MelCumsumMagDeepTied        W=5, 8L, n=90, 40ep                  93.0      25,032\n\n\n\nA.5   Cumsum Acoustic Front End\n\nThe main paper uses log-mel features because they remain the strongest acoustic representation in the current\nexperiments. The cumsum front-end experiments test a separate question: whether the same prefix-sum\nmechanism can replace the FFT/mel front end while preserving streaming computation from raw audio.\nThe front end maintains running complex sinusoidal sums over waveform samples and emits either log\nmagnitude alone or log magnitude together with the real and imaginary channels.\nTable 11 summarizes the standard 10 ms hop setting. The strongest cumsum front end uses frozen mel-\nspaced phases and a learned linear bottleneck from [log |c|, Re c, Im c] to the CNN input channels. This\nreaches 95.2% test accuracy. Within the cumsum front-end family, frozen mel-spaced phases outperform\nlearned phases in this sweep, and retaining phase-carrying real and imaginary channels improves over log\nmagnitude alone.\n\n\nTable 11: Cumsum front-end ablation at hop 160 samples. All rows use 80 acoustic channels and the same\nCNN backend.\n                Model                          Front-end features      Window   Best val     Test\n                MelCNNMaxPool                  FFT + log-mel              400      96.4      97.1\n                CumsumSpec, frozen phases      [log |c|, Re c, Im c]      400      95.2      95.2\n                CumsumSpec, frozen phases      [log |c|, Re c, Im c]      160      95.2      94.8\n                CumsumSpec, learned phases     [log |c|, Re c, Im c]      400      94.0      93.9\n                LearnedSpecCNN                 log |c|                    400         –      93.4\n\n\nTable 12 repeats the comparison in a no-overlap hop-400 setting. This setting makes the phase channels\nmore visible: with learned phases, adding real and imaginary channels raises test accuracy from 90.8% to\n93.6%; with frozen phases, it raises test accuracy from 92.0% to 94.0%.\nTable 13 adds a related learned-filterbank diagnostic. The convolutional sin-cos filterbank uses Hann-\nwindowed filters rather than a running rectangular cumsum window. The strongest configuration in this\nsweep is the frozen mel-spaced log-magnitude filterbank. This contrasts with the cumsum front end in ta-\nble 12, where real and imaginary channels help because the running cumsum magnitude is a noisier spectral\nestimate.\nTable 14 reports the corresponding end-to-end cumsum sequence models that replace both the acoustic front\nend and the temporal backend with cumsum layers. The same pattern appears there: log magnitude is\n\n\n                                                      11\n\fTable 12: Cumsum front-end ablation at hop 400 samples, where adjacent acoustic frames do not overlap.\n                    Model               Front-end features             Phases    Best val    Test\n                    MelCNNMaxPool       FFT + log-mel               fixed mel        95.3     95.4\n                    CumsumSpec          [log |c|, Re c, Im c]     frozen mel         94.1     94.0\n                    CumsumSpec          [log |c|, Re c, Im c]         learned        94.0     93.6\n                    CumsumSpec          log |c|                   frozen mel         92.7     92.0\n                    CumsumSpec          log |c|                       learned        92.2     90.8\n\n\nTable 13: Sin-cos convolutional filterbank front-end ablation at hop 160 samples. All rows use the same\nCNN backend.\n       Model                                Front-end features                                    Test      Params\n                                                    2         2\n       FilterbankSinCos Frozen              log(sin + cos ), frozen mel filters                      95.7   25,628\n       FilterbankSinCosMagReIm Frozen       [log |c|, sin, cos] → Linear, frozen mel filters         95.4   30,468\n       FilterbankSinCos Learned             log(sin2 + cos2 ), learned filters                       94.7   57,628\n       FilterbankSinCosCombined Learned     [log |c|, sin, cos], learned filters                     94.5   61,468\n\n\na useful anchor, while carrying real and imaginary channels gives the next layer access to within-window\nphase.\n\n\nTable 14: Mag+re+im ablation for raw-audio cumsum stacks. These models use cumsum front ends followed\nby cumsum temporal layers.\n               Model             Test     Params        Feature path\n               CumsumE2EMag      93.5     62,732        mag+log front end; complex cumsum layers\n               MagDeep V2        92.8     71,556        [log |c|, Re c, Im c] all layers, with projection\n               MagDeep V2        92.5     63,812        log-mag first layer, then [log |c|, Re c, Im c]\n               MagDeep V1        90.5     65,084        log-mag only, wider model\n               MagDeep V1        89.2     33,692        log-mag only, smaller model\n\n\n\nReferences\nGuy E. Blelloch. Prefix sums and their applications. Technical Report CMU-CS-90-190, School of Computer\n Science, Carnegie Mellon University, 1990.\n\nSeungwoo Choi, Seokjun Seo, Beomjun Shin, Hyeongmin Byun, Martin Kersner, Beomsu Kim, Dongyoung\n  Kim, and Sungjoo Ha. Temporal Convolution for Real-time Keyword Spotting on Mobile Devices. In\n  Proc. Interspeech 2019, pp. 3372–3376, 2019. doi: 10.21437/Interspeech.2019-1363.\n\nAlbert Gu and Tri Dao. Mamba: Linear-time sequence modeling with selective state spaces. arXiv preprint\n  arXiv:2312.00752, 2023.\n\nAlbert Gu, Karan Goel, and Christopher Ré. Efficiently modeling long sequences with structured state\n  spaces. In Proc. International Conference on Learning Representations, 2022a.\n\nAlbert Gu, Ankit Gupta, Karan Goel, and Christopher Ré. On the parameterization and initialization of\n  diagonal state space models. arXiv preprint arXiv:2206.11893, 2022b.\n\nAnkit Gupta, Albert Gu, and Jonathan Berant. Diagonal state spaces are as effective as structured state\n spaces. In Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems, volume 35, 2022.\n\nChristin Jose, Joe Wang, Grant Strimel, Mohammad Omar Khursheed, Yuriy Mishchenko, and Brian Kulis.\n  Latency Control for Keyword Spotting. In Proc. Interspeech 2022, pp. 1891–1895, 2022. doi: 10.21437/\n  Interspeech.2022-10608.\n\n\n                                                         12\n\fByeonggeun Kim, Simyung Chang, Jinkyu Lee, and Dooyong Sung. Broadcasted Residual Learning for\n  Efficient Keyword Spotting. In Proc. Interspeech 2021, pp. 4538–4542, 2021. doi: 10.21437/Interspeech.\n  2021-383.\nDaniel S Park, William Chan, Yu Zhang, Chung-Cheng Chiu, Barret Zoph, Ekin D Cubuk, and Quoc V Le.\n SpecAugment: A simple data augmentation method for automatic speech recognition. In Proc. Interspeech\n 2019, pp. 2613–2617, 2019. doi: 10.21437/Interspeech.2019-2680.\n\nOleg Rybakov, Natasha Kononenko, Niranjan Subrahmanya, Mirkó Visontai, and Stella Laurenzo. Streaming\n  Keyword Spotting on Mobile Devices. In Proc. Interspeech 2020, pp. 2277–2281, 2020. doi: 10.21437/\n  Interspeech.2020-1003.\nJimmy T. H. Smith, Andrew Warrington, and Scott W. Linderman. Simplified state space layers for sequence\n  modeling. In Proc. International Conference on Learning Representations, 2023.\n\nJianlin Su, Yu Lu, Shengfeng Pan, Ahmed Murtadha, Bo Wen, and Yunfeng Liu. RoFormer: Enhanced\n  transformer with rotary position embedding. arXiv preprint arXiv:2104.09864, 2021.\nAshish Vaswani, Noam Shazeer, Niki Parmar, Jakob Uszkoreit, Llion Jones, Aidan N Gomez, Lukasz Kaiser,\n  and Illia Polosukhin. Attention is all you need. In Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems,\n  volume 30, 2017.\nPete Warden. Speech commands: A dataset for limited-vocabulary speech recognition. arXiv preprint\n  arXiv:1804.03209, 2018.\nNeil Zeghidour, Olivier Teboul, Félix de Chaumont Quitry, and Marco Tagliasacchi. LEAF: A learnable\n  frontend for audio classification. In Proc. International Conference on Learning Representations, 2021.\n\nYundong Zhang, Naveen Suda, Liangzhen Lai, and Vikas Chandra. Hello edge: Keyword spotting on\n  microcontrollers. In Proceedings of Machine Learning and Systems, 2018.\n\n\n\n\n                                                   13\n\f", "numLines": 673, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 673}}}
